@Sotto Voce, @WR, @Zeb, @B, @Barry Ancona, and @G! 

Hey, I didn't get back to the comments very quickly Thursday night, perhaps blame the happy hour...ssss, so I also want to give a quick shout out to those of you who answered my comment Thursday night about how I can never remember AGORA -- I think your suggestions and the conversation may actually do the trick this time! I've long known what agoraphobia means but, weirdly, I had never thought about the root of the meaning. Many thanks to you all! Now I can't wait for it to show up in another puzzle! 

Also, @Barry Ancona, to answer your question, though it wasn't enjoyed that evening, the answer would always be ouzo! I have some very fond memories of ouzo evenings with friends. And probably some lost memories, I'm guessing...  

@G, I'm honored to be who you think of with bad voice to texting! 😘

@B I did Friday in half the time this took me. 


……

Emus need their own emoji 🦜

@Mr Dave 

It might be a "made up" thing.  They're called speed bumps in the East as well.  I've never heard it called humps.

/emus think speed bumps are still dirty but more painful

@Mike 

If you penne this as a play and do the lighting, maybe you could rigatoni.



🏆  (Emu, maybe you could ziti this one out)

@Paul 

That’s a good way to put it. 

For me, it often comes down to one answer that I need to get to unlock a section of the grid. Maybe it’s some Harry Potter reference, or “Seinfeld,” or just some clever wordplay that I can’t sort out. And while I’m struggling, everyone else is breezing through those answers.

@Andrzej 

Sorry. That SE corner was just plain hard. 

If I’m not mistaken, it’s noon in Warsaw as I write this. That’s not too early for a beer on a Saturday, is it?

@Eric Hougland 

I'm on holiday in Germany so no time is too early for ein Bier 🥰🍺






Post length tax. Nothing to see here.

@Al  in Pittsburgh 

No, the whole point was not to call out that the word being referenced was Spanish.  Some of us, like me, didn't know it. (I guessed from the similar French.). The clues are written in English, so e.g. (accepted English using Latin obviously) is appropriate I think.

/emus speak pig latin

@Vaer 

The part about Julia Child was more interesting. 

I have enjoyed Amy Adams in lots of other roles, so I may have had my expectations too high for “Julie and Julia.”

@Shrike 

COMO was a gimme for me because I vaguely remember seeing it 30+ years ago. But does jOMO look like a Spanish word?

I did get SHAPERS only with a lot of crosses.

@Heidi 

Sorry to hear that. Sunday is almost certain to be easier. 

Good luck and stay cool!

@mlpse 

Some breeds such as poodles come in a “toy” variety that is smaller than the standard variety for the breed.

It’s a nice clue because even people who know more about dogs than I do probably don’t immediately think of animals when they hear the word “toy.”

@CCNY 

Hey, Taylor, I mean CCNY...I was thinking Thursday how that lyric could have been used to clue the cross to EMEND (not amend), which was ITS ME. Some people thought the [Indentifying words from a familiar voice] could have easily been ITS MA...which it couldn't have been if they'd have used the Taylor Swift lyric.

Or the old Todd Rundgren lyric...Hello, ITS ME...

@L. Eaglesham 

NO BACKSIES came straight out of my childhood and into the grid -- and I'm no youngster. 

About 30 years ago, there was a road sign that got a laugh out of my mother every time we passed it: it was printed SOFT SHOULDERS, to which someone had scrawled below "firm thighs". (My mother is in the same decade as you...) Today's clue definitely got a chuckle out of me!

@Rich in Atlanta 
My little brother Ric went to a JAMBOREE one year--held at Valley Forge--so that was a helpful gimme, but I went down by the bow eventually (10 wrong letters --or blanks)...found it quite difficult...

I find I am in Good Company

@Rich Treta 
LOL  I got that on the crosses!  Some SOLVER, I am!

Stay cool....

@Simcha 
I think Mu is talking about the NYT app not the Games app.

@Mu
Get rid of the Times app, read through a browser. 
Install Games app, follow Simcha's instructions.

@Ernest 
Agreed on the Medina’s
Now if the answer had been funky cold…

@HeathieJ

Ditto, I absolutely tore through the puzzle and hit a brick wall in the SE, I spent more time there than solving the entire puzzle, haha. I did manage to set a new PB so it worked out in the end.

Sometimes you're on the same wavelength as the constructor and the answers are obvious. Sometimes you aren't and you can't find a toe hold anywhere. I don't think it's unreasonable to struggle with a puzzle that doesn't click with you, I have a few constructors that are on my skip list because I don't enjoy their cluing. It's all relative in the end.

@HeathieJ 

I inherited the box set of Curb Your Enthusiasm's first few seasons a while back, and during covid lockdown, we commenced watching. My partner is a huge Larry David fan and was really into it. I, on the other hand, gave up after a few episodes -- though am always available to watch clips he brings to my attention!

And I'd like to clarify: at no time did I call my GPS anything that could be construed as bundt cake! Though I'm not nearly as nice to mine as you are: point proven lol.

@Krists Andersons 

Yes, we are in your walls.  

We all like your latest haircut.

@Les 

I agree in general. Too many names and terminology in that corner. 

I liked most of the puzzle, but not that section.

@Megan 

That's funny, a couple of people echoed you, but I found the upper left significantly slower than the upper right (though the whole puzzle was fast).  Dirty mind was easy, Like Water for Chocolate was a name as I'd heard it, pretty much everything was known to me.  But in the upper left I was thinking Santa for toys and lodes and ores for miners and ponders for thinking and Ore Ida for fries, so that one took a minute.

/emus hit the mother lode

@Caitríona Shanahan 

What? No love for Van Morrison? Is he DQed for having been born in Northern Ireland? Or just before your time?

Slippery elm (ulmus rubra) is native to the northeastern United States, so that might explain why you have not heard of it.

